    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w33466</id>
    <title>A Cognitive Theory of Reasoning and Choice</title>
    <updated>2025-02-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Pedro Bordalo, Nicola Gennaioli, Giacomo Lanzani &amp; Andrei Shleifer</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We present a theory of decisions in which attention to the features of choice options is determined by the decision maker's categorization of the current choice problem in a set of problems she solved in the past. Categorization depends on goal-relevant as well as contextual problem-level features. The model yields systematic heterogeneity in attention and choice in a given problem based on different past experiences, rigidity of choices when categorization does not change despite new data, and discontinuous shifts when changes in bottom-up salient features cause re-categorization. The model unifies major puzzles and framing effects in riskless, statistical, and lottery choice based on heterogenous and unstable mental representations.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w33466"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2025-02-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
